PRESIDENT TO OPEN VIRGINIA-BASED IRISH CONFERENCE AND FESTIVAL
- President Mary McAleese will be the keynote speaker at "Re-
Imagining Ireland - Transformations of Identity in a Global
Context" which will take place at the University of Virginia
and a number of other venues in Charlottesville from May 7 to
10.  The conference and festival, funded by the US National
endowment for the Humanities, Ireland's Cultural Relations
Committee and others, will feature more than 100 journalists,
writers, politicians, artists, scholars and musicians.  The
focus of the conference, directed by Andrew Higgins Wyndham,
will be on the changing profile of Ireland both North and South
in a global context.  Further information on the event can be
accessed at: http://www.re-imagining-ireland.org/

QUB RESEARCH TEAM'S PROGRESS IN COMBATING BREAST CANCER
- A research team at Queen's University Belfast is attempting to
define the function of a gene known as BRCA1, which guards the
body against cancerous cells, in a study of the incidence of
breast cancer.  Led by Dr Paul Harkin, the team is working to
understand how defects in the gene, which is known to play a
role in repairing damaged DNA, can prevent it from identifying
and destroying cancerous cells.  By replacing BRCA1 into cancer
cells, the team is hoping to reactivate its ability to destroy
cancer cells which have been exposed to the molecule interferon
gamma.

INTERNATIONAL RECOGNITION FOR UU PHOTOGRAPHER
- Nigel McDowell, a photographer who works in the Faculty of Life
and Health Sciences at the University of Ulster, has had one of
his photographs selected by Kodak for its "Picture of the Day"
feature.  Mr McDowell's photograph of a Mexican tree frog,
which was taken to illustrate a medical research story, has
also been used by the University for advertising and promotion.
On Tuesday of this week the photograph, which can be viewed at
http://www.kodak.com*, was featured on the Kodak electronic
billboard in New York's Times Square. *Search for Picture of
the Day Winner for January 07 2003

ENVIRONMENTALISTS MEET AT NUI, GALWAY
- The 13th Irish Environmental Researchers Colloquium is taking
place this week at NUI, Galway, hosted by the university's
Environmental Change Institute.  "Environ 2003", the annual
meeting of the Environmental Sciences Association of Ireland,
will address methods of environmental management and the steps
being taken by those responsible for environmental policy.  The
conference, which has attracted some 300 delegates, will be
officially opened by university Registrar Professor James
Browne and keynote speaker Eamon de Buitlear will give a
lecture entitled "Life in the Wild".  For details see
http://www.nuigalway.ie/news/dialann.php3?d_id=755

CALL FOR PAPERS (IT&T 2003) AT LETTERKENNY IT
- The call for papers has been announced for the third annual
conference on Information Technology and Telecommunications
(IT&T 2003) to be held at Letterkenny Institute of Technology
on October 22 and 23 this year.  The theme for this year's
conference is the Convergence of Communications, Computing and
Mobility and papers on a broad range of research themes
relevant to the conference will be welcomed. Further details
can be found at www.ittconference.com/call2003.html

UU JOINS HEALTH EDUCATION PARTNERSHIP
- The University of Ulster has entered into a UK Healthcare
Education Partnership with the Royal College of Nursing, City
University, the University of Leicester andBritain's
eUniversity.  The partnership will deliver a portfolio of
online learning programmes for healthcare professionals, with
the first of the programmes to be launched in September of this
year.  Heading the team from UU is Professor Clive Mulholland,
Professor of Technology Enhanced Learning, while the
partnership is chaired by the RCN's Executive Director for
Nursing, Alison Kitson. Further information at:
http://www.ulst.ac.uk/news/releases/2002/673.html


